Merge pull request #39 from ibuildingsnl/more-reliable-exit-code-determinationMake system-under-test exit code determination more reliable

Make system-under-test exit code determination more reliable@remyhonig was experiencing failing system tests that worked fine on Ubuntu systems; the test harness couldn't reliably determine the system-under-test's exit code. After `strace`ing the hell out of `expect`, I've determined that `expect`'s `wait` command hangs up on the system-under-test (`SIGHUP`), which, in many circumstances, just aborts the PHP script and just returns an exit code of 0. I haven't been able to determine why it did work on Ubuntu, yet not on Mac. It does appear that the `wait` command is not made specifically for making assertions about the spawned process' exit code.nnTo address the issue, I have replaced the `wait` command with an `expect` command call which expects a certain magic string, which contains the exit code, to appear. While it is a hack, it is very reliable, and someone must be out for breaking things if he/she would use this magic string in QA Tools' output.n

Hide Composer output unless something failsThe first attempt was based on the assumption that Composer errors are output on standard error, and diagnostic messages (Installing X, Installing Y, etc.) on standard out. It turns out all diagnostic output is written to standard error, unless it is truly an answer to the question (like how `composer licenses` outputs the list of licences on standard out).nnThe implemented solution hides all Composer output, unless something goes wrong.nnThe implemented solution became too complex to maintain in the Makefile (it was already quite complex), so this commit moves it to a dedicated build script.n

The commit hook no longer runs on a temporary directoryThe qa-tools are now run on the current directory. This is a compromisenfor speed, since speed is the most important factor for adoption andnusage of these tools.nnBefore, the qa-tools would be run on a temporary directory thatnaccurately reflected what was going to be committed. This setup is idealnform a perspective of robustness and representativeness, but was rathernslow.nnAs a compromise, committers are now reminded when there are unstaged ornuntracked changes that could influence qa-tools results. They have tonconfirm to continue running the qa-tools and commit.n

Explicitly allow colorized outputIn order to allow colorized output, it might be better to explicitly allow interpretation of backslashes using the `-e` parameter.rnrnSee `man echo`:rnrn```rn   -e enable interpretation of backslash escapesrnrn   -E disable interpretation of backslash escapes (default)rn```rnrnThis way it also works for people having `-E` as default.

Fix pre-commit hashbangWhen running the git pre-commit hook in my bash terminal, I get the following error:rnrn```shrn$ git commit -mKeep uploads shared between releasesrn.git/hooks/pre-commit: 29: .git/hooks/pre-commit: [[: not foundrn```rnrn(and on various other lines, all including `[[`). Turns out the pre-commit hook is ran in `sh`: `#!/bin/sh`. However `[[` is bash only: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/12230690/string-comparison-in-bash-not-foundrnrnMy `/bin/sh` is linked to dash, not bash. I can easily solve this by re-linking sh to bash, however I might not be the only one having this. Better would be to just use `#!/bin/bash` as this pull-request does.
